  "statement": "# Meeting Rooms\n\nReturn whether one person can attend all meetings without overlapping intervals.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: intervals = [[0,30],[35,40],[45,50]]\nOutput: true\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: intervals = [[7,10],[2,8]]\nOutput: false\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: intervals = []\nOutput: true\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return the value described by the method signature.",
  "editorial": "Track the local choice that leaves the most room for future choices, or sort intervals so conflicts can be resolved with one pass.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def canAttendMeetings(self, intervals):\n        intervals.sort()\n        return all(intervals[i][0] >= intervals[i - 1][1] for i in range(1, len(intervals)))\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Sort first when relative order drives the decision.",
    "Keep the smallest state that proves future feasibility."
  ],
